[Morarji Desai]]{{efn|name=Desai|Desai had earlier abolished the awards while he was in the office of Prime Minister for it being \"worthless and politicized\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-toi/special-report/The-great-Bharat-Ratna-race/articleshow/2714556.cms|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140517172013/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-toi/special-report/The-great-Bharat-Ratna-race/articleshow/2714556.cms|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 May 2014|title=The great Bharat Ratna race|newspaper=The Times of India|date=20 January 2008|accessdate=17 May 2014|author=Mukul, Akshaya}}</ref>}}\n|[[Gujarat]]\n|[[P. V. Narasimha Rao]],[[Indian National Congress]]\n| Independence activist Desai was the fourth Prime Minister of India (1977\u201379).<ref name=\"pm\"/> He is the only Indian national to be awarded the [[Nishan-e-Pakistan]], highest civilian award given by the [[Government of Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2001/jul/11spec.htm|title=When India and Pakistan almost made peace|date=11 July 2001|accessdate=13 September 2015|author=Bhatia, Shyam|publisher=Rediff.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710140448/http://www.rediff.com/news/2001/jul/11spec.htm|archivedate=10 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\" | 1992\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Maulana_Abul_Kalam_Azad_1988_stamp_of_India.jpg|100px]]\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background-color:#CEE8F0;\" | [[Abul Kalam Azad]]{{efn-lr|Abul Kalam Azad died on 22 February 1958, at the age of 69.}}{{efn|name=Azad|Earlier, Abul Kalam Azad had refused the Bharat Ratna while he was the [[Ministry of Human Resource Development (India)|Education Minister]] of India (1947\u201358) citing that the selection committee members should not themselves be the recipients.<ref name=\"aticon\">{{cite web|title=India's top award misses congeniality|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/JA24Df01.html|newspaper=