12}} film-maker Ray is credited with bringing world recognition to [[Cinema of India|Indian cinema]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sight and Sound Poll 1992: Critics|publisher=California Institute of Technology|url=http://alumnus.caltech.edu/~ejohnson/sight/1992_1.html|accessdate=3 February 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016212355/http://alumnus.caltech.edu/~ejohnson/sight/1992_1.html|archivedate=16 October 2013}}\n* {{cite web|title=A Slanted Canon|author=Kevin Lee|publisher=Asian American Film Commentary|date=5 September 2002|url=http://www.asianamericanfilm.com/archives/000026.html|accessdate=3 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/684ysTg3l?url=http://www.asianamericanfilm.com/archives/000026.html|archivedate=31 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}\n* {{cite web|title=Greatest Film Directors and Their Best Films|publisher=Filmsite.org|url=http://www.filmsite.org/directors5.html|accessdate=3 February 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331180201/http://www.filmsite.org/directors5.html|archivedate=31 March 2014}}\n* {{cite web|title=The Greatest Directors Ever by ''Total Film'' Magazine|publisher=Filmsite.org|url=http://www.filmsite.org/greatdirectors-totalfilm2.html|accessdate=3 February 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426215114/http://www.filmsite.org/greatdirectors-totalfilm2.html|archivedate=26 April 2014}}</ref> In 1984, Ray was awarded the [[Dadasaheb Phalke Award]], India's highest award in cinema.<ref name=\"dadasahebdff\">{{cite web|title=Dadasaheb Phalke Awards|url=http://dff.nic.in/dadasahebphalke.asp|publisher=Directorate of Film Festivals|accessdate=6 May 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526044918/http://www.dff.nic.in/dadasahebphalke.asp|archivedate=26 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\" | 1997\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Gulzarilal_Nanda_1999_stamp_of_India.jpg|100px]]\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Gulzarilal Nanda]]\n|[[Punjab]]\n|[[H D Deve Gowda]], [[Janata Dal]] Coalition\n| Independence activist Nanda was two times interim Prime Minister of India (1964, 1966) and two times deputy chairman of the [[Planning Commission (India)|Planning Commission]].<ref name=\"pm\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/1998/jan/15nan.htm|title=Former PM Gulzarilal Nanda dead|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=14 September 2015|date=15 January 1998|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052853/http://www.rediff.com/news/1998/jan/15nan.htm|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Aruna Asaf Ali 1998 stamp of India.jpg|100px]]\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background-color:#CEE8F0;\" | [[Aruna Asaf Ali]]{{efn-lr|Aruna Asaf Ali died on 29 July 1996, at the age of 87.}}{{sup|{{Hash}}}}\n|[[West Bengal]]\n|[[Inder Kumar Gujral]], [[Janata Dal]]<br />{{small|(''[[United Front (India)|United Front]]'')}}\n| Independence activist Ali is better known for hoisting the Indian flag in Bombay during the [[Quit India Movement]] in 1942. Post Independence, Ali was elected as Delhi's first mayor in 1958.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-aruna-asaf-ali-1331351.html|title=Obituary: Aruna Asaf Ali|newspaper=The Independent|author=Singh, Kuldeep|date=31 July 1996|accessdate=14 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925133653/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-aruna-asaf-ali-1331351.html|archivedate=25 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |[[File:Abdul_Kalam_2015_stamp_of_India.jpg|100px]]\n! scope=\"row\" | [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]]\n|[[Tamil Nadu]]\n|[[Inder Kumar Gujral]], [[Janata Dal]]<br />{{small|(''[[United Front (India)|United Front]]'')}}\n| Aerospace and defence scientist, Kalam was involved in the development of India's first satellite launch vehicle [[Satellite Launch Vehicle|SLV III]] and was the architect of [[Integrated Guided Missile Development Program]]. He worked for [[Indian National Committee for Space Research]], [[Indian Space Research Organisation]], [[Defence Research and Development Laboratory]] and was appointed as the Scientific Advisor to the Defence Minister, Secretary to Department of Defence Research and Development and Director General of [[Defence Research and Development Organisation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/profile/apjak.html|title=Bio-data: Avul Pakir Jainulabdeen Abdul Kalam|publisher=Press Information Bureau (PIB)|date=26 July 2002|accessdate=12 May 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513081337/http://pib.nic.in/profile/apjak.html|archivedate=13 May 2014}}</ref> Later, he served as the eleventh President of India from 2002 until 2007.<ref name=\"president\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" | 1998\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:M._S._Subbalakshmi_in_\"Sevasadan\".jpg|100px]]\n! scope=\"row\" | [[M. S. Subbulakshmi]]\n|[[Tamil Nadu]]\n|[[Inder Kumar Gujral]], [[Janata Dal]]<br />{{small|(''[[United Front (India)|United Front]]'')}}\n| [[Carnatic music|Carnatic classical vocalist]] Subbulakshmi was from [[Madurai]], [[Tamil Nadu]]. She is known for her divine voice & often hailed as \"Queen of songs\",the first Indian musician to receive the [[Ramon Magsaysay award]] for her public service. She was honoured as a resident artist Aasthana Vidwan of Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanam. Tirupati Urban Development Authority (TUDA) has installed a bronze statue of her in the city. Her many famous renditions include the chanting of Bhaja Govindam, [[Vishnu Sahasranamam]] (1000 names of Vishnu), Hari Tuma Haro, Venkateswara Suprabhatam (musical hymns to awaken Lord Balaji early in the morning), Annamacharya Sankirtanas and Tamil [[Tevaram]]. She also acted in a few Tamil films in her youth from 1938\u20131947. She donated many of the royalties on several best sold records to many charity organisations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2004/dec/11ms2.htm|title=M S Subbulakshmi: 'Nightingale' of Carnatic music|publisher=Rediff.com|date=12 December 2004|accessdate=23 September 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708075137/http://www.rediff.com/news/2004/dec/11ms2.htm|archivedate=8 July 2015}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/getahead/slide-show/slide-show-1-specials-ms-subbulakshmi-commemorated-with-a-doodle/20130916.htm|title=M. S. Subbulakshmi commemorated with a doodle|publisher=Rediff.com|date=16 September 2013|accessdate=30 October 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131223175805/http://www.rediff.com/getahead/slide-show/slide-show-1-specials-ms-subbulakshmi-commemorated-with-a-doodle/20130916.htm|archivedate=23 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Chidambaram_Subramaniam_2010_stamp_of_India.jpg|100px]]\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Chidambaram Subramaniam]]\n|[[Tamil Nadu]]\n|[[Inder Kumar Gujral]], [[Janata Dal]]<br />{{small|(''[[United Front (India)|United Front]]'')}}\n| Independence activist and former [[Minister of Agriculture (India)|Minister of Agriculture]] of India (1964\u201366), Subramaniam is known for his contribution towards [[Green Revolution in India]]. During the late 1970s, he worked for [[International Rice Research Institute]], Manila, and the [[International Maize and Wheat Improvement Center|International Maize and Wheat Research Institute]], Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|title=C Subramaniam awarded Bharat Ratna|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/1998/feb/18cs.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|date=18 February 1998|accessdate=12 May 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203092215/http://www.rediff.com/news/1998/feb/18cs.htm|archivedate=3 February 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"4\" | 1999\n| align=\"center\" |[[File:Jayaprakash Narayan 1980 stamp of India bw.jpg|100px]]\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background-color:#CEE8F0;\" | [[Jayaprakash Narayan]]{{efn-lr|Jayaprakash Narayan died on 8 October 1979, at the age of 76.}}{{sup|{{Hash}}}}\n|[[Bihar]]\n|[[Atal 